Bombarder in the name of morality?
NEW YORK – Eloquence has always been one of the main assets of American President Barack Obama.
Yet it seems today that his words have cornered him in a trap.
After saying in March last year that the United States 'would not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against the Syrian people' and mentioning last year a 'red line' that should not be crossed, Obama would lose face if he does not react energetically to the murder, attributed to the Syrian regime, of more than 1000 civilians using sarin gas.
Of course, the risk of losing face is not a valid reason to attack another country.
But why did Obama get himself entangled with such rhetoric in the first place?
Why this particular line?
US Secretary of State John Kerry is right to call the use of gas 'moral obscenity'.
But torturing children, a prelude to civil war two years ago, is just as much so.
And is it morally more obscene to kill civilians with chemicals than to bomb them, shoot at them, or starve them to death?
It is commonly admitted, since the use of mustard gas during World War I, that some weapons are more immoral than others.
Mass destruction weapons, especially the nuclear bomb, certainly cause more damage and more quickly than conventional weapons.
But is there really a clear moral distinction between killing around 100,000 people with a single atomic bomb at Hiroshima and killing even more people in a single night at Tokyo using incendiary bombs?
Was it more immoral to gas the Jews than to shoot them in mass graves?
An argument, defended notably by Nicholas Kristof of the New York Times, holds that a swift punitive action could convince Syrian President Bashar al-Assad to give up using chemical weapons and return to "more mundane means of massacring his people".
To my mind, this makes no sense.
The question is surely that of the massacre, not the methods used.
In any case, moral indignation, however justified it may be, is not a sufficient reason to go to war.
Mao Zedong was responsible for the death of more than 40 million Chinese in the 1950s and 1960s.
No sane person has suggested that a military intervention in China was a good idea.
In the 1980s, Saddam Hussein gassed hundreds of thousands of Iranians and Kurds – with the support of the United States.
Is it, therefore, a legal question? The use of chemical weapons is in fact a violation of international conventions, including the Convention on the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, which Syria never signed, and the Geneva Protocol, of which it is a party.
There are, therefore, valid reasons to consider Assad a war criminal, in which case he should be indicted by the International Criminal Court (ICC), established, let it be said, by a treaty that the United States never ratified.
But bypassing the United Nations and launching an illegal war to punish an illegal act is not easily defensible policy.
One might, however, argue that the "international community", or Western countries, or the United States as the main Western power, must surely draw a line somewhere.
How can responsible governments simply turn a blind eye when thousands of innocent people are being massacred?
Tolerating a genocide is not acceptable.
But where exactly does one draw the line?
How many murders constitute a genocide?
Thousands?
Des hundreds of thousands?
Millions?
Or does the number not come into account?
Genocide is after all a matter of intention, there is a will to kill or persecute individuals due to their race, ethnic affiliation, or belief.
In principle, killing ten people for these reasons – or even two – would constitute a form of genocide.
The problem can be approached from another angle.
The question to think about before intervening militarily in a country is whether this action has a chance to improve the situation, save lives, and make the world a safer place.
Yes, violence against civilians, whether through sarin gas or combat helicopters, is a moral obscenity.
Responding to it implies asking: what is the best solution?
Justice and morality have little to do with such a decision.
Like the action of the ICC, "humanitarian intervention" has a greater chance of producing results in a weak country (for example, Serbia, Mali, or Sierra Leone) than in the case of a great power.
No one would contemplate missile strikes on China or Russia in the name of human rights defense or to enforce international norms and conventions related to war.
Syria, as many have pointed out, is not Libya or Mali.
It is not a great power either.
But the civil war raging there has already spilled over its borders, involving more important countries, including Iran, Turkey, and Russia.
There is no doubt that a regional conflagration would be infinitely worse than the moral obscenities of a civil war.
It is not absolutely certain that an American intervention would reduce the risk of a wider conflict.
Indeed, some proponents of an American intervention – both neoconservatives and 'liberal hawks' - seem to want the opposite: they are calling for a war with Iran.
And Obama probably established a link in his mind between the red line concerning Syria and that which he had drawn for Iran, perhaps in the same unreflective manner, to prevent it from developing nuclear weapons.
What can we expect from American strikes on Syrian targets, when Obama has already indicated that they were not intended to bring down the Syrian regime?
They will not bring an end to the civil war.
But a single missile will be enough to make the United States a direct participant in this war, sparking a surge in violence.
Taking this risk to save Obama's honor does not seem particularly wise.
This point of view is shared by many Syrians, including among the rebels.
This is the opinion of most Europeans.
And of a majority of Americans.
This is perhaps even Obama's opinion, which is why he is desperately trying to gain time by delegating to the US Congress the authorization to use armed force in Syria.
Since his entry into office, his relations with Congress have been far from easy.
But he needs it more than ever today to cover his back.
